07615nam a22009255i 9789048551064DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20212020ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485510647 a10.1515/97890485510642doi  a(DE-B1597)576201  a(OCoLC)1253313927  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 4aDP96 7aHIS0370102bisacsh04a946.0122304aThe Visigothic Kingdom :bThe Negotiation of Power in Post-Roman lberia /ced. by Panzram, Paulo Pachá. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2021] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (408 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLate Antique and Early Medieval Iberia ;v900tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tIllustrations -- tAbbreviations -- tPreface and Acknowledgements -- t1. The Visigothic Kingdom of Toledo -- tThe Day Before - Prologue -- t2. Late Roman Spain -- tConcepts of Central and Local Power -- t3. The Visigoths in Hispania -- t4. The Early Visigothic Presence in Southeastern Hispania -- t5. Beyond Central and Local Powers -- t6. King Wamba's Campaign against dux Paulus (673) -- tPower, Identity, and Ethnicity -- t7. How to Stay Gothic without a Gothic King -- t8. Who are the Visigoths? -- t9. The Visigothic Kingdom - A Kingdom without Visigoths? -- t10. Local Citizenships and the Visigothic Kingdom -- tRepresentations of Power -- t11. Recopolis -- t12. Figura et potentia Coin and Power in the Visigothic Kingdom -- t13. The Liber Iudiciorum -- t14. Epigraphic Habit and Power in Visigothic Hispania -- tPower and Church -- t15. Between Throne and Altar -- t16. Ecclesiastical Landscapes in the Visigothic Capital and Countryside of Toledo (Spain) -- t17. Ancient Classics and Catholic Tradition through Time and Space -- t18. Conflicts over Episcopal Office in Southern Hispania -- tThe Day After - Epilogue -- t19. In a Savage Kingdom (regnum efferum)? -- t20. Conclusions and Future Perspectives -- tIndex of Places, Names and Subjects0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aHow did the breakdown of Roman rule in the Iberian peninsula eventually result in the formation of a Visigothic kingdom with authority centralised in Toledo? This collection of essays challenges the view that local powers were straightforwardly subjugated to the expanding central power of the monarchy. Rather than interpret countervailing events as mere 'delays' in this inevitable process, the contributors to this book interrogate where these events came from, which causes can be uncovered and how much influence individual actors had in this process. What emerges is a story of contested interests seeking cooperation through institutions and social practices that were flexible enough to stabilise a system that was hierarchical yet mutually beneficial for multiple social groups. By examining the Visigothic settlement, the interplay between central and local power, the use of ethnic identity, projections of authority, and the role of the Church, this book articulates a model for understanding the formation of a large and important early medieval kingdom.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0https://www.aup.nl/en/publish/open-access  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 4aAntiquity. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aMedieval Studies. 4aPolitics and Government. 4aSociology and Social History. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aVisigoths, Iberian Peninsula, Late Antiquity, Early Middle Ages, Toledo.1 aArce, Javier, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrassous, Laurent, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCabrera, Rafael Barroso, econtributor.4